    <p component="3040">
      This course develops techniques from two extraordinarily disparate mathematical disciplines.
      While these two disciplines often study related problems, the techniques are cleanly bifurcated.
    </p>

    <p component="3080">
      This course focuses on proofs of important results in calculus, which we previously have been using without proofs in areas of limits, continuity, sequences, series, differentiation, integration, and infinite series. 
    </p>
    
    <p component="3086">
      This course can be divided into two parts.
      In the first, we cover the basic definitions and examples of a group, subgroups, quotient groups, homomorphisms, group actions, and important theorems about the structure of certain groups such as Sylow's Theorem and the Fundamental Theorem of Finitely Generated Abelian Groups.
      In the second, we encounter basic definitions and examples of rings, subrings, ideals, quotients of rings, homomorphisms, and other topics as time permits.
    </p>
